Feb 21 2009 	Beautiful Hotel for Couples...	This is a beautiful complex with some of the nicest and most helpful staff I have ever met. The room was immaculate, cleaned everyday, fresh towels, toiletries, newspaper, fruit bowls and fresh flowers, fresh bottled water, all complementary, every day. The pools are temperature controlled and there are three: one is deep and very warm, one is large - excellent for older kids and adults alike and there is a kids pool, also excellent. All are immaculate. Free loungers and beach towels, poolside or beach, are placed for you, even down to the towels being laid out. The beach is well kept with boogie boards etc. There are several full-time lifeguards who are especially vigilant with children. If you want watersports go out from the hotel, turn right onto the public part of Jumeirah beach and you'll find them there - that beach is massive, stretching for miles.The restaurants at this hotel are not child friendly, indeed several do not permit children at all, except for at breakfast time. There is nowhere ideal to take the children in the evening on the complex either. For example, one of the bars that is next to a kid's mini playground is closed (in February anyway!). The food is expensive generally, alcohol expensive too, and not good if you have a budget! You will find many people access the hotel, especially at weekends to use the facilities and the restaurants that are not residents so it can feel that you have no exclusivity. However, whilst people can come in to the restaurants (very late as well) it should be noted that their bags are searched on entry and they have no access to the hotel rooms so you are safe. Note that parts of the complex are noisy till late. Watch out for shifty billing from the beach bar. The menu may say something is 18 dhms but you will probably get charged 38 dirhams, because you were looking at the wrong menu, even when they gave it to you! A beer was 27 dhms on the menu but billed at 35 dhms. We were charged £24 for 3 juices on our first day! The staff at the beach bar were quite ignorant about this when we complained but a quick word with the hotel manager corrected this. There are no children's menus anywhere and no children sized portions of food or drink available at all. If money is an issue for you, or if you like good value for the money you spend, go out of the hotel, turn left and eat at Japengo's. You'll get Japanese noodles, Iranian and Lebanese food - platters are awesome, pizza or pasta there so it suits everyone (despite the lack of alcohol). TAXIS: The cream coloured cabs are half the price of the white cabs. SOUKS: Take a taxi to the Gold and Spice Souks in the Bur Dubai area - if your driver looks baffled about where you want to go, ask for the Bur Dubai bus station and then ask a local where to get the Abra boats from - it's near HSBC bank if you need a landmark. You can take a boat across the manmade canal/river to the Souk - this will cost you maybe 1-2 dirhams (20-40p) and adds to the fun. When you get there, ask another local where the Gold Souk is, you probably won't ever find it otherwise....the Spice Souk is near - ask in the shops, people are almost always happy to help you. Leave enough time to take an Abra boat back over then as you disembark walk over to your left - there is an Iranian Souk there too. Don't expect to find any restaurants in these areas, although drinks are readily and very cheaply available either from drinks machines or local people with trays! Expect to pay 2 dhms (40p) for a canned juice.Go to Madinat Jumeirah (near the palm).....it's a new Arabian Souk, pricey but nice to wander. Suggest you go to Japengo's there as well as it's halve the price of the other eateries. You can take a short Abra boat tour of the &quot;new Venice&quot; which is quite pleasant. You're near the Jumeirah Palm in this area, short taxi ride, I would say. DESERT SAFARI. If you don't do this with Alpha Tours then when other people tell you how great it is you'll be gutted. Dune Bashing - even for young kids - is fantastic, you eat Arabic food, try traditional costume, have henna, sheesh, belly-dancing, camel riding and more. It's very good value and will suit anyone. Alcohol is available and is reasonably priced.I must say, I was surprised to see people query the rating of this 5* hotel. This is a fair rating. Can't see why anyone would say otherwise. It has all the facilities and service you would expect of a 5* hotel. Good pools, good facilities, a spa, massage area on the beach....I could go on....	
Jan 3 2009 	5* you're kidding!!!	If you're looking for the luxuries and extras that come with booking a 5* hotel then Dubai marine Beach Resort should be given a wide birth.My wife and 11 year old daughter and our friends with their 2 children aged 5 and 4 were left with little choice when booking late for a Winter break but took some comfort in the fact that this hotel was rated 5* and was in Dubai, where we have previously stayed in various hotels.The Restaurants and Resort area appear to be a totally seperate enterty to the hotel and are mainly used by locals. There are numerous late night bars that don't close until 3am making certain rooms within the hotel susceptable to noise from late night music and homegoing revellers. The local Mosque is also extrememly close and would wake all but the very heaviect of sleepers at 5.30am every morning with the call for prayer.The rooms although clean, were very average despite being called &quot;Suites&quot; and came with none of the little extras you would expect. We were offered an upgrade to an Executive suite which we were told were slightly bigger then the Junior suites and had Balconies and Jacuzzi baths. Well, the Balconies had no view to speak of and didn't have any furniture on them, rendering them completely useless. The seperate Lounge area was used as a 2nd bedroom for the kids by means of a sofa bed which was left as a bed all week. There were no other chairs provided therefore nowhere to sit whilst getting ready to go out.The TV channels were restricted and picture quality poor.The choice and quality of food offered in the various restaurants was acceptable however, we were obliged to stay on a Half Board basis and were not advised of the arrangements on arrival. Basically you are given vouchers which can be used in 6 of the 8 restuarants (the remaining 2 are owned not owned by the Hotel). These vouchers entitled us to a choice from a set menu. However, we were made to feel like second class citizens when presenting the vouchersand were told that the children had to leave the restaurants by 9.30pm which is disgraceful for a hotel purporting to be family friendly.The pools and grounds generally are in urgent need of refurbishment and the waiter service virtualy non existent. The Tropical pool made my daughters hair and various swimming costumes turn green, which although totally unacceptable and never really explained, was compensated by the refund of our room upgrade.On checking out, our bills contained numerous spurious beverage charges which could not be accounted for and although deducted, we were not given satisfactory explanation.I cold go on, however to summarise, if you want to pay 5* prices for 3* service and accommodation then this hotel is for you. If not, stay well clear.	
